# ASR Collections — Cursor Project Rules

## Stack (do not deviate without flagging it first)
- Next.js 14, App Router, TypeScript (strict mode)
- Tailwind CSS — brand colors already defined in tailwind.config.ts:
  brand.plum #5C1F35, brand.rose #8C4A5E, brand.blush #F5E3E6,
  brand.blushDark #ECCDD3, brand.mauve #9C6B57, brand.white #FFFFFF
- Fonts: font-heading = Playfair Display, body = Inter
- Supabase (@supabase/supabase-js) for database — client lives at lib/supabase.ts
- Cloudinary for all product images (cloud name: hzxrxgf1, unsigned preset:
  asr_products) — never Supabase Storage for images
- No payment gateway. No OTP/SMS verification. Checkout is a WhatsApp
  redirect (wa.me link), not a payment flow.

## Source of truth
- The PRD (ASR_Collections_PRD.md) and asr_collections_schema.sql are the
  spec. If a prompt asks for something that conflicts with either file,
  implement what's asked but add a comment flagging the conflict — do not
  silently change the schema or the PRD.

## Code conventions
- Functional components with hooks. Named exports, not default exports.
- Server components by default; only use "use client" when the component
  genuinely needs interactivity or browser state.
- Absolute imports with @/ prefix.
- Mobile-first Tailwind: unprefixed classes = mobile layout, sm:/md:/lg:
  scale up only.
- No gradients, drop shadows, or glow effects on brand UI elements — flat
  design throughout.

## Safety rails (non-negotiable)
- NEVER delete or overwrite .env.local, package.json, or any file in
  /supabase without explicit confirmation first.
- NEVER run destructive SQL (DROP, TRUNCATE, DELETE without a WHERE clause)
  against Supabase without stating exactly what it does and getting
  confirmation first.
- NEVER add a new npm dependency that wasn't explicitly requested, without
  asking first.
- Before importing any package, verify it's actually installed
  (`npm list <package>`) rather than assuming from training data.
- Before any multi-file change, create a git checkpoint first:
  `git add -A && git commit -m "checkpoint: before <task>"`.

## Output quality
- Zero placeholders. Never leave `// TODO: implement this` or
  `// rest of the code here` — either fully implement a function or clearly
  say why you can't and what you need to proceed.
- Be concise. Don't explain standard/obvious code patterns unless asked.
- After any change, state exactly how to verify it worked (a command to
  run, a page to check) — not just "this should work now."

## Scope discipline
- Only touch the files named in the current prompt. If a fix genuinely
  requires touching an out-of-scope file, say so before doing it.
- One task per prompt. Don't bundle unrelated changes into a single edit.
